messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

This does not solve the underlying issue which is that network writes can block some of the read paths, but it does try to minimize it.
I chose not to fix all the overlaps since the remaining ones while not complicated doesn't solve the overall issue. There are potential places where forward progress will be halted. This requires more thought rather than fixing the locks.

encodingHeaders/encodeTrailers did identify an interesting issue with buffer sharing. I chose just to extend the write lock to guard it versus copying the buffer. It does mean we will halt earlier rather than on the write if the network is blocked.

Abandoned

I realized my testcase is flawed and hides the fact that this too has the same issue since I am using the write lock.
I am working on not holding both, but it breaks other tests which rely on underlying locking behavior.

Patch Set 1:

I understand the issue a bit better now and I don't have a good solution.

The order of requests matter because of the hpack's dynamic table for headers. We cannot split the encodeHeaders and writeHeaders since we must guarantee the order.

Patch Set 2:

There are still two outstanding issues probably related. Both TestTransportGroupsPendingDials and TestTransportDisableKeepAlives_Concurrency dial too often.

Patch Set 2:

I did solve the remaining issue. The headers must be sent in order of stream id. The easiest way to guarantee this is to obtain the write lock during the read lock. This cannot be done since we may cause a the connection pool to block. One solution is yet another lock just to sequence this.
The more I think about this, the more I wonder what problem we are solving. The only case that we are fixing is when a new connection will be created otherwise reusing one of these write blocked connections will just block.
Patch Set 5: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 5:

While there is one remaining issue the overall locking is much improved. I don't see any point in holding this up just to fix the last item which is more difficult to fix properly.
